  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) was launched and assembled in space over a series of missions that spanned several years. The project began in the early 1990s, with the first module launched in 1998. Here\u2019s a brief timeline of key events related to the launch and assembly of the ISS:\n\n1. **Initial Agreements**: The ISS is a collaborative project involving multiple space agencies, including NASA (USA), Roscosmos (Russia), ESA (European Space Agency), JAXA (Japan), and CSA (Canada). Initial agreements were made in the early 1990s to create the space station.\n\n2. **First Module (Zarya)**: The first module of the ISS, named Zarya (Functional Cargo Block), was launched on November 20, 1998, by a Russian Proton rocket. Zarya provided power, storage, and support for the station.\n\n3. **First American Module (Unity)**: The second module, Unity (Node 1), was launched on December 4, 1998, aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour (STS-88). Unity connected to Zarya and provided additional attachment points for future modules.\n\n4. **Assembly in Orbit**: Over the following years, several missions were conducted to add more modules and components to the ISS. Key modules included:\n\n   - **Zvezda** (Service Module) launched on July 12, 2000\n   - **Destiny** (U.S. Laboratory Module) launched on February 24, 2001\n   - **Columbus** (European Laboratory Module) launched on February 7, 2008\n   - **Kibo** (Japanese Experiment Module) which was launched in three parts, with the first part on March 9, 2008\n\n5. **Continuous Assembly**: The ISS has been continuously inhabited since November 2, 2000. The assembly of the station involved more than 40 space shuttle missions and the delivery of multiple modules from various nations.\n\n6. **Ongoing Expansions**: The ISS continues to evolve, with new science experiments, hardware upgrades, and additional modules being added. The development phase has largely concluded, but maintenance and upgrades are ongoing.\n\n7. **Current Status**: As of 2023, the ISS remains a key platform for scientific research, international cooperation, and technology development in low Earth orbit.\n\nIn summary, the ISS was launched and assembled through a series of missions starting in 1998, culminating in a collaborative international effort that continues to adapt and maintain the station for scientific research and exploration missions.",
